We first extract the key values from the data and then calculate each ratio step‐by‐step.

1. Current Ratio  
 • Total Current Assets (end) = 9,717,259.46  
 • Total Current Liabilities (end) = 1,493,246.99  
  Current Ratio = 9,717,259.46 / 1,493,246.99 ≈ 6.51

2. Gross Profit Margin  
 • Gross Profit = 2,329,939.23  
 • Total Revenue = 5,064,939.23  
  Gross Profit Margin = (2,329,939.23 / 5,064,939.23) × 100 ≈ 46.00%

3. Debt to Asset Ratio  
 • Total Liabilities, in this case, equal the Total Current Liabilities = 1,493,246.99  
 • Total Assets (end) = 15,200,446.16  
  Debt to Asset Ratio = 1,493,246.99 / 15,200,446.16 ≈ 0.10

4. Net Profit Margin  
 • Net Profit = 707,199.17  
 • Total Revenue = 5,064,939.23  
  Net Profit Margin = (707,199.17 / 5,064,939.23) × 100 ≈ 13.96%

5. Cash to Current Debt Ratio  
 • Cash on Hand = 4,540,900.90  
 • Bank Deposits = 2,866,063.83  
 • Sum of Cash = 4,540,900.90 + 2,866,063.83 = 7,406,964.73  
 • Current Liabilities = 1,493,246.99  
  Cash to Current Debt Ratio = 7,406,964.73 / 1,493,246.99 ≈ 4.96

6. Free Cash Flow (FCF)  
 • Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities = -64,099.10  
 • Cash Flow from Investing Activities (Purchase of Fixed Assets) = -528,936.17  
  FCF = Operating CF + Investing CF = -64,099.10 + (-528,936.17) = -593,035.27

7. Return on Assets (ROA)  
 • Net Profit = 707,199.17  
 • Total Assets (end) = 15,200,446.16  
  ROA = (707,199.17 / 15,200,446.16) × 100 ≈ 4.65%

Thus, the final answer is:

  }
